comment_Rating: Dr. Lexow's seminar courses all have the same general format where you analyze primary literature about that week's topic. There is a reason why Dr. Lexow's classes have long wait lists each year. Her class taught me a range of skills that will be essential to me as I aspire to become an informed biomedical professional. comment_Rating: Great teacher!! Dr. Gillion makes class fun and interesting.  He is definitely one of the best young professors at Penn...plus he is pretty hot.
Very helpful, learned a lot from his class. A little ADHD though... gave many drawings as assignments at the same time. But excellent critiques and feedback. Great teacher.

An excellent teacher, who coaches & encourages each student according to his or her abilities.He weaves into the course work information regarding artists' whose work is insttructive with respect to the subject being covered in class.He takes the class on field trips to sites on campus for drawing & for exposure to other classes.A gifted teacher.
Kind of intimidating.
great prof. would recommend
Extremely knowledgeable in his field. Always very helpful in class and outside of class.
Excellent professor. Hard grader and a challenging course (CIS320) but I learned a lot in a very short amount of time

Not just a terrible prof, a horrible person too.  Condescending, insulting, and actually told one of my friends in the class that he should reconsider being a PhD student at Penn if he was struggling with Khanna's class. Absolutely wonderful educator. Passionate and knowledgeable, funny and charming. Values and respects students. Possibly a little too dreamy.
Interesting reading. Uninspiring politics. Toes the line. Passive aggressive

He's an excellent teacher that truly made bearable and enjoyable a period of literature I'm truly not fond of. He's extraordinarily helpful and I highly recommend him if you have general requirements to fill or are an English major or just interested in the class.
Inaccessible, double standards, does not support students with disabilities.

Professor Kaul is a articulate and clear lecturer,however, he talks about Freud a lot for an English professor. His grading is a bit harsh, but there aren't many assignments aside from the weekly readings.
Very very intelligent guy, a bit stubborn about his ideas though. Tough grader.

Max's class is notorious for having students either hate it and never take it again, or taking it over and over throughout the rest of their college career. Regardless, his feedback can be applied to anyone's work, even if what you produce doesn't match the particular style he's looking for.
He is practically a mainstay of the T 1:30-4:30 slot. Very fair advice on fiction work, although it seems clear what he desires from a short story (ie. can occasionally teeter on the restrictive)

Eisenberg is AWESOME. Super nice guy, great sense of humor. You'll learn a lot, laugh a lot, he's challenging but the workload isn't too intense. He'll reward you if you work hard. I definitely felt like I really understand the basics of probability and it's helped me tremendously in my other courses. TAKE ANY OF HIS CLASSES IF YOU CAN!
An amazing and dedicated real estate professor.
I hate research, but I like Professor Lukens.  He managed to take boring/abstract concepts and apply them to daily clinical practice.

His agenda is to teach critical thinking, and he will take the most dry topic and spin it any way he can to generate interest and engagement.  He isn't afraid to deviate from the day's lesson to discuss the subject in its larger philosophical and political context, and he's not afraid to ruffle feathers to provoke thought.  As good as teachers get.
best professor ever
I think he's great teacher not because I aced the subject because what he taught us was very useful in my research afterwards.
omg...zzzzzzzzzzz....he should stick to research or WHATEVER....not a good teacher AT ALL!

Great professor who cares about his students. If you memorize everything from the note packets he gives in class, you can get a very high score. Out of the four midterms, only one was especially hard, covering material we didn't cover in class (but he curved the class to account for this). Easy A

Gomaa is a really entertaining lecturer, and I found that the more attention I paid the more the material stuck in my head (even as a firm social sciences student). Don't take if you're socially anxious - he WILL make you engage with the class. The tests are absolutely insane.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment_Rating: Lectures were interesting and entertaining. As a social science major, this is the first hard science class that I've ever enjoyed. It's nothing but memorization and the tests are easy as long as you study.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Professor is disorganized, unprofessional, and acts inappropriately toward women in class.

Unprofessional. Prints his slide deck but slides are out of order, the content is different, etc. Even exams are poorly constructed - entire groups of questions are duplicates. I love Omar! Great class, funny, organized, informative. Exams tedious and very long, asked for every little bit of minutia he mentioned in lecture.
Classes were informative.  Professor very nice.  Only 3 tests.  no other work required.  But tests, although multiple choice, VERY EXTENSIVE.  Some information asked not on slides.

I had Prof. Lassiter in 2003 and he is by far one  of the best professors in the school. The school is afraid of teachers like him because he speaks the truth and he is student centered and does nor maintain status quo.

The ENTIRE class is in Italian which makes it very difficult for first time learners. You can only speak in Italian as well. Also, she expects you to participate A LOT! She's a nice lady but she makes it a too hard for a beginner's class.
He may be a brilliant mathematician, but he is a horrendous professor.  I have never disliked a class more than his.
A very nice and cute professor.

KC is one of my favorite professors at Penn. He was very willing to help and every time I went by his office he always made an effort to get to know me. If you can, I recommend you take him in a small seminar class; that kind of environment is where his talents really shine through. He is a tough but very reasonable grader.

My favorite professor at Penn. Learned a lot from his class. His lecture notes made all the hard-to-read philosophy easy to understand. The papers that we had to write were a little stressful, but we had a choice of topics.
Class would be even better if Prof relied less on book.
Only rated 5 for easiness because I took AP Macro in HS and couldn't really gague the difficulty since I already knew about 1/2 the material.  Solid prof though
He's a genius. Also really funny, but not easy to communicate with.
Great teacher, explains everything well and goes beyond the lesson to impart other important tidbits of information on the class.
Excellent teacher who brings a career of experience and knowledge to the classroom and greatly enhances the helpfulness of the course.

LT Giles did a great job teaching us what was need to be known. A power point heavy class but it was the best way to teach all the information needed.  He brought in other people in the Navy and Marines to teach specific subjects of their field.  Great class, learned a lot.
LT Giles does a great job making sure the students learn the most important aspects of being in the Navy.  He is very helpful and very practical.
I can tell Lt. Giles is very experienced and he makes the knowledge very easy to understand. His class is very useful, I only expected to learn a little more about the other Navy communities.
Great teacher. Explains things well and a very enjoyable class.
LT Giles is a great professor and has some ridiculous "sea stories." Great, informative class.
He is very informative and is always ready to discuss current events. He will teach you exactly what you need to know, because he has experienced much of it himself.
Very Intelligent, he tells you exactly what he expects and wants you to know.
great teacher, lots of experience in the Navy and knows what he's doing. Keeps the class interesting and starts class the same way with current events on most days.
Good teacher, knows what he's talking about when it comes to Naval Science.
Great class and teacher!
Very helpful and knowledgeable on everything we did.
Good class, too early!
I agree with the rest of the comments. He is an excellent teacher, I really enjoyed this class!
LT Giles is very knowlegable and really knows how to keep a class interested. Highly recommended!
He's not even a full professor and he's the best teacher I've ever had.
Great class! Very interesting teacher!
Very good instructor. Too many powerpoints, but not really his fault.

I performed well throughout the whole semester, and if it wasn't for the final being ridiculously hard, then I would have gotten an A. But no, instead I got a B. No one was able to finish the final exam. She should have at least been very lenient when grading the final for that reason. She doesn't know how to grade. She only looks at percentage.
Great lectures, very interesting class. Easy if you do the reading. Highly recommended.
Wonderful! Will certainly miss the interesting lectures. Requires lots of reading, but both the reading and lectures are worth it.

She is overgenerally defensive. Students said program feels competitive, and she said, 'its not'. (It is, and not talking about it doesnt help.) She is also director and dedicated to promoting IEDP to enroll new students. Program and class feel cliquey and superficial
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Group projects--Graded by few things

ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Tough but so worth it
Awesome prof! Awesome class! (a lot of work)
Awesome professor, really listens to students. You can tell she really loves what she does.  She has an End of semester gathering/party at her house...two thumbs up.

Dr. P was very interested in making sure that we got the most out of her class. Although the work was hard, she was always willing to help by staying after class and setting up appointments. She regularly checks her e-mail. If you do the work and apply yourself, you're sure to get an A.

Very enthusiastic and knowledgeable professor. Lectures are well organized and taught in a refreshing interactive style (maybe include too much information at times). Assignments are challenging and time-consuming (homework on current topics every week, various lecture quizzes, three exams), but definitely worth the effort. I learnt a lot

Great guy who is passionate about the subject matter. Funny & engaging, lectures are entertaining most of the time but monotonous when nobody answers his questions. When they do though, this class is a lot of fun. Sometimes doesnt explain things well so it will take textbook reading. Tests on DETAILS from slides. Def understand but need 2 memorize2

Dr. Sanders definitely knows his stuff. And he is quite helpful. However, his exams are really tough, especially the in-class parts (the take-home parts are tough too, but you have a week to solve the problems). Overall, hard but good.
I think Dr. Sanders did a fine teaching job in this course. And he was very helpful if I had any questions. I would recommend biotechnology majors to take this course.
The course was very challenging (especially the exams), but the topics were always presented clearly and interestingly. I would recommend taking this course.
Overall I think that Dr. Sanders did an excellent job in teaching lecture and lab. I would recommend taking him as an instructor for both course parts combined. This is a wonderful opportunity.

It was a challenging course, but very structured, organized, and well-taught. There are four lecture sections, each concludes with a discussion of specific problem set. The exams consist of an in-class and take-home part. I really loved the take-home questions
Great teacher, very fair, clear and organized.

This is a very hands on class. Prof M is very engaged and makes a big effort to convey difficult material in ways that are accessible. Linking the lectures to the labs is hard but he goes out of his way to play videos, show demos, and have "tear downs" of things like kindles and playstations where you get to see how real world electronics are built

He was the most intellectually stimulating professor I have ever had. His class is not very assignment heavy which frees you up for actually learning more. It's very discussion based so people are encouraged on their own to do the readings because the topics are refreshing and applicable. Very racially and socially conscious person. Love his class!
Great professor. Really enjoyed his lectures.

It's great the way he dances around the issue like a true politician. Also, he tries to be unbiased - which is good, aside from the occasional leftward slip. He doesn't do any of the grading, and discusses 30 pages of reading in less than 1 minute - unclear guy.

This class is absolutely excellent. Dr. Smith is unbelievably helpful. He handles a controversial subject matter with complete objectivity in grading and respectfully brings humor into traditionally charged topics. Easily the best professor I have ever had.

In the two classes I've taken with Professor Butler, I have adopted a new passion and appreciation for RS at Penn. She is intuitive, openminded, and considerate on towards all students (as long as you are respectful and go to class!!!). She is passionate and involved with what she teaches. She is helpful with assignments and exams.

She is more interested in imposing her opinion and making sure white guilt is felt than actually teaching anything. Made consistent errors that could be pinpointed by her students and took herself so seriously that she would get angry if you questioned her and would insinuate that racism/sexism was the "real" reason why you raised a question.
Not good at all :/
Pathetic. This teacher is pathetically bad at her supposed job. Do not give this untalented instructor any more classes. Bad.

She is an awful teacher who thinks that she knows everything when half of the time she is making mistakes in the names of the things she is trying to teach! I'm a student and even I can see her mistakes! She takes herself way too seriously, and her TAs are awful! Her and her TAs are very harsh graders, beware!

So... Casey is absolutely brilliant. You're expected to participate, yes, but it's hard not to. Her lectures are relevant, interesting and thought provoking. Also encourages the class to be sensitive of students from varying backgrounds/opinions, etc. Not a tough grader (from my experience). If you have a chance to take a class with her, do it!
Casey is an excellent professor. I enjoyed taking her class and learned a great deal.
Incredible! Casey is so knowledgeable and relatable, and she always made class interesting with discussions, projects, etc. 10/10 would recommend.

Casey is a pretty good professor. Shes very cool and laid back. We have lots of discussions. Tumblr and twitter project can be a bit annoying but the most you will do is read a lot and one big paper at the end

She was awesome! Some of the assignments were not fully developed and so were confusing but I think it'll get better as she fine-tunes them. She was very passionate and brought up relevant examples which really helped with engagement. She used various modes of teaching ie videos, lecture, class discussion, student presentations, etc.

Knowledgeable but honest when she doesn't know.  Manages to make a pretty dry topic into an interesting 2.5 hours every class.  Plus if someone ever tried to bust in and take you hostage she could handle them!
Casey is one of the most wonderful professors at SP2 she is super helpful!
Casey is very energetic and knowledgeable. She looks for creative ways to engage the class, which everyone really appreciates. Of all my classes, this is the one I truly look forward to each week.

If you are looking for well-rounded advanced clinical material, do not take this class. No critical thinking encouraged, it was a waste of time and money. She has no time outside of class and has told students that she was too busy to write recommendation letters.
She speeds through lessons. Doesn't explain anything

Contrary to other reviewers, I had a good experience with Dr. Krawchuk. I took her in an elective, while some of the more negative reviews seem to have been from folks in mandatory seminars. I found her to be a competent prof, and very good at facilitating discussions. She does give lots of group projects, so if that isn't your thing look elsewhere
Not a star professor ... Mediocre instruction. A true disappointed.

Seems nice but isn't really. Becomes angry and condescending when people disagree with herself. Is EXTREMELY dismissive. Bills herself as a ''grief and loss' expert'''; she has an esteemd mentor who allows her to write in his books but hadn't published/researched on the topic. Low quality instruction. offers "help" but too "busy" to offer it...

She only knows about medical social work, as that's all she has ever done. If one wants a well- rounded orientation to Advanced Clinical Social Work, it would behoove him or her to take a more well-rounded and knowledgeable professor. I literally had to fact check everything she said...

Mediocre instruction. She is all over the place and lacks "conceptual clarity." At the end of the semester, most students stated that they felt as if they were not grounded in theory and therefore unprepared for the profession. Students of other clinical professors felt MUCH more prepared.

Just began this semester and am loathing this class... I have a BSW and liked social work before attending her class. I learned more at the BSW level; she isn't challenging me or making the subject interesting. Please DON'T!

teaches at a VERY basic level, for example, only says one general statement about slides and is not one for detail.  as a result, she does not cover the material/content well.  she expects students to read (since she can't teach...) but does not discuss the readings in class!  Perfect class for an easy A but not so perfect for 'real' learning...

She's very nice and all but I could not stand her teaching style. She talked over students and kind of had a savior complex that was extremely annoying. She could be really disorganized as well and that was frustrating. I would not take a class with her again.
Very clinically oriented. Has private practice for grief therapy. Great at teaching clinical skills and very compassionate
Jane is one of the, if the the best teacher I have ever had, you will succeed in her classes unless you intentionally work towards failing
Fabulous professor, brilliant woman...and super helpful. I went to this class worried about the requirement and am leaving it really interested in geology. My fave course this semester.

Dr. Willenbring is the best!  She is super inspiring and in the class she talks about all the good parts of Geology and none of the boring stuff.  Def my favorite class this term.  Have to go to class during the add period though.

Easily the best professor I have taken in my freshmen year at Penn. I learned quite a bit even though I don't really care about the subject. Although this class isn't easy, if you pay attention and read the book an A is attainable. I thoroughly reccomend taking her class.
She was great! Very funny and super helpful. I was dreadding this requirement but I'm really glad I took it.

Great professor, very interested in class - Ethics. Topic based, and many modern works detailed (Kant, Hobbes, etc.) and additionally modern-day articles and research (fMRI, etc.). 2 straightforward papers and final consisting of about 20% questions from list given beforehand. Not too work heavy, great professor.

Terrible lecturer, terrible quality of lecture recordings, have found multiple mistakes on slides over and over, not to mention the fact that the slides themselves show low effort in construction and care.
Simply the best instructor in the biology department.
Not very helpful, a lot of book reading for major clarification.
She is the most engaging, passionate and caring professor I have met. Take a moment to ask her about her pets and family - you won't be disappointed!
Might as well just read the book. Nothing new; nothing controversial; everything politically correct. Waste of time.

The worst part is this class could have been amazing, but Dr. H is completely incompetent. Reads directly off the (unintelligible) slides, gives no explanation of her grading system, completely incompetent at teaching. I dont understand how she got this position. The only benefit is the class is easy because she doesnt know ANYTHING about the topic

If there is such a title as a cyber samurai this prof is it. He is a far cry from all the other profs who just preach. This prof does a lot of deep show and tell. He is also a real internetwork expert and cyber hacker. He recommends key books but honestly he should be teaching the guys who write the books. He is an expert++ and demands precision.

Hardest class I have taken. You need to know everything - servers, routers, switches, vmware, programming, bits, bytes. Prof knows all this inside and out - has real world practical experience. You will get no credit for something that sort of works - class demands very high level of precision and perfection to become a cyber kung fu master.

For professor the network either works or not - very binary 1 or 0. No partial credit after so much work. Always available to help understand concepts but you need to put in lots lots  of effort and show you want to learn. All classes hands on and  shows you so many tricks. Part of DoD cyber warrior program - pretty serious stuff.
clear on assignments and easy on grading.  easy work load for the week.

Professor is way passionate about security and really knows it inside out. His eyes and red lips get way intense when he is so focused on topic. Prof is always online 2am, 5am, 10pm - doesn't matter he can do a conference call anytime. He needs perfection so you need make sure you learn the material and core concepts.

Very very hard to get an A in this class. Instructor is always helpful and I always get response in less that 5 minutes. Instructor is a real cyber and internet expert - he teaches but also does detail show in class. No credit for attendance like other classes but if you want to learn you need to show up or you lose a lot.

The professor is quite open to discussion and  the class shows how to use the security tricks. He is not big on deadlines but be careful - if you don't do the work in time you will be lost on the next week's homework. Make sure to submit all papers before last day of class and you are good. Don't expect to get any credit for showing up to class.

She was awesome! I can say her advice was instrumental in graduating from this amazing school. While nearly all the professors were great! She stood out. She is passionate about her work! And it shows!

Probably one of the more gifted instructors at Penn GSE, and likely the most expert in qualitative research. I took her twice and enjoyed both courses. I learned a ton. She's equally accessible to doctoral and master's students. Lots of stuff for different learners, including group projects and individual work.

Ravitch is an excellent professor! She not only provides a wealth of perspective, she communicates it very well (which translates into student comprehension), and she has a passion for the subject. While the course could be difficult to wrap the mind around if you're new to qualitative research, she makes info accessible to her students.
One of the best profs I've had at Penn.  Great at playing devil's advocate to get you to shore up your arguments.
She was ok, but a lot of her outside of work opinions leaked into class and it was embarrassing at times. She demonstrated very poor judgement and it made me lose trust in her.

One of the best professors Ive ever had. Very nice, but politely applies pressure when necessary. She is an expert in stylistics, grammar and effective writing. (Always consider your audience!) She is very open-minded and willing to learn from her students. Class was nearly always full of productive discussions. Absolutely take her course!
Excellent teacher on so many levels.  Clear and organized thinking  while deeply insightful about the content.  Got a lot from taking her. Fave teacher at Penn hands down. (senior now)
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: Been going through and rating some of my favorite professors so someone hopefully benefits and enrolls in one of their classes.  Val is awesome.  Just take anything she teaches.  usually it's "study of an auteur" about a filmmaker...forgot the course number
Better than average
Extremely hard to hear would be my only complaint...very soft-spoken.
Really tough prof, be aware.  Good, but tough and math-intensive.
Amazing teacher.  Rad.  Knows a ton.  This was an advance Spanish class, but I learned much more than Spanish (he usually teaches Literature and Cultural analysis). Take him!
Awesome, awesome guy with a cool life story.  Take classes with him.  Not sure if he is still around but he was the head of my study abroad program.
Awesome, awesome guy with a cool life story.  Take classes with him.  Not sure if he is still around but he was the head of my study abroad program.

Prof. Miner is basically this super-cool soft-spoken American woman who spent much of her life in India and not teaches kids at Penn how to play sitar.  And the class is extremely fun.  Highly recommended.

Took a creative writing class with him my Freshman year.  He used to write for Rolling Stone, and I think he just published a book.  Easy grader, always has fun stories to tell during class, and insightful.
Professor is pretty unaccommodating. During campus covid outbreaks when most have moved finals online, we are the one bastion of covid risk.

Took the Econ version of Game Theory with him (I understand he also teaches a more qualitative GT class for the poli sci department...I'm sure it's equally interesting if not more interesting).  Thick French accent, but if you can't deal with accents you shouldn't major in Econ lol.  Thought I'd add him since I enjoyed the class

May seem like a weird thing to say, but I loved the way he made his tests...they weren't easy but they were fair and made you think creatively.  There tends to be a lot of rote memorization in intro Bio and he managed to avoid that.  Cool accent too.
Pr. Mitchell is awesome.  Brilliant and a true teacher.  I took her City in South Asia class and will take her other class this semester.
Got to be honest -- took this class because it fulfilled requirements.  But it was a real revelation.  Learned a lot and the Professor knows Indian history inside and out and teaches it with passion.
Took Rise and Fall of the Third Reich with him.  Doesn't quite live up to the hype, but then again, how could anything?  The class is famous for a reason.

Even though editing is such a painful topic to learn about, Dr. Rogers made it fun and engaging. He is always enthusiastic about teaching and he is actually a funny guy. He's very knowledgeable and helpful if you reach out to him. He's probably been my favorite English professor during my time at PSU.

If you get him for your English 15 class, you are very lucky! His assignments are straight forward, so if you follow the guideline you should get a good grade. He is extremely helpful and will meet with you as much as possible. He understands that you are freshmen students and will not be perfect writers. He is all around a great teacher!

Really awesome teacher. His lectures/discussions are really interesting and gets the class involved. However, be ready to speak in class. His assignments are not hard at all, but he does expect them to be done well. Funny guy though, great class. If you have to take this class, take it with him.
He was great. Very engaging. The material was a little dry, but he did a great job of clarifying it in class.
Really great.  The best TA I've had at Penn.  If you have a choice, pick him.

Harry is the BEST TA ever!!!!! I actually love him! He is the best and so helpful and i wish he would be my TA forever!!!!! he helps me with math every day and his office hours are SO helpful!!!!!!! Definitely be in his class!!!!!!!!!! YES!!!!!

Dr. Farnsworth is a very knowledgeable and energetic professor, never staying in one place. Class was not mandatory, but she timely posted audio recordings of every lecture online. Highly recommend any class with Dr. Farnsworth!
Extremely helpful and clear. Great professor
Great teacher, explains things really well.
Great educator with a passion for his field
She is the worst teacher I ever had. Avoid her class at all costs!
She goes out of her way to make sure struggling students can understand the material and will make sure that they find a niche among the students who are doing better.
Her teaching was only clear to students who already knew the material.  She does not clearly explain concepts to intro-level students.  Needs to cater to all student levels

On the plus side, the building his lab is in is new and has got better equipment. However, he is extremely rude to students and is very difficult to reach even through email. The norm is that he will ignore you throughout your entire experience working with him. Definitely does not provide a good laboratory experience.

Prof. Ribeiro is an absolute legend - his well timed jokes makes his lectures enjoyable. He manages to elucidate the material to his students very well. I'd say take his class even if you have no interested in majoring in EE/SSE. You'll definitely learn A LOT and have a FUN time!
ESE 224 is the most amazing class I've taken at upenn. Prof. Alejandro is an adept lecturer.
GOOD professor, hard at times but helpful in understanding of material.

Larry Hirschorn taught the Psy.in Organizations course and was more interested in preaching than he was teaching.He was also non-responsive to emails and did not teach at the calibur I would have expected from an ivy league university.We also sat through at 9-5class where we did nothing but look at one another with no agenda.This class was useless!

I think you get out of this course what you put into it.  Although I did get an A (I think), I fell like I spent a lot of time working on this class which doesn't totally apply to my major.  So I don't know if Id recommend it.  He certainly has flare.

Professor Jerolmack's enthusiasm, availability, and willingness to help are phenomenal. I learned so much in this course, and the field trip is spectacular. The assignments can be challenging, but the class notes and readings are all you need for the course. This course was one of the best courses I took while at Penn.
Awesome teacher. She really cares about students' progress. Highly recommend!!
One of Penn's best assets
Hard Professor but very interesting. He knows everything about game theory. Would definitely suggest him.

If you interested in Prof. Dixon-Roman's areas of research and study, I would advise you read some of his articles or consult one of his books.  However, as a course instructor he is incompetent. He cares only about his research and has zero concern for his students learning experiences.

Scotty is a solid professor. Easy going and nice. Gives helpful feedback. Don't miss the critiques because you will miss out on important feedback and information that will help you in the class. Would def take another class with him.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Easy-going, cool guy. Will definitely help you if you need it. Encourages individuality and is big on progress over the course of an assignment, meaning he wants to see you improve from feedback (whether his critique or that of your peers). Chill and fun!
Love her lecturing style!
Dr.  Apicella's lectures are entertaining and informative. She delivers the material in a way that keeps you interested and is also easy to understand.
Excellent professor! Loved her class.
Prof. Keene requires hard work and high-level synthesis of difficult legal concepts. Very interesting discussions on regulatory takings.

Urban Law. Professor Keene is a truly brilliant professor. Educated at Harvard Law and Yale undergrad, he exemplifies the very best of a Penn professor. Demands hard work. Great introduction to real estate law. Gives you a sound grounding for torts, property, and civil procedure if you ever decide to enter law school. Know FIRAC.Research paper/exam
My favorite TA to date.  Very nice guy.  Extremely helpful!

Darkroom photography is incredibly difficult and time consuming but Kelsey made it the highlight of my year. I am still keeping up with my photography and have started a website for my work. She took the time, six months later to write a glowing recommendation letter for me and is a professor who has gone the extra mile to help me.
Great lecture giver, she knows her stuff, she will explain really well. You are well prepared for tests. She is willing and ready to help in any way possible.
She is a great lecturer, has a great sense of humor, and is very willing to work with her students.
She helped me get jobs and further my career and was a great mentor overall.
Terrible.  Used the "R" word in class.  Incomprehensible. Offensive, and culturally insensitive.
She is an amazing teacher!! She helped me with all my troubles!!! If you guys take her course, you will find an excellent job!!

Ditty brings an upbeat mood to class. His lectures are entertaining, helping students stay engaged. With little effort, Ditty comes up with many great examples of each concept we cover; he's very knowledgeable. He is also approachable, welcoming any and all questions students may have. To me, he is one of the best professors at SP2.

Professor Ditty is extremely knowledgeable when it comes to the subject of this course: DBT. There was a lot of information packed into this semester course, and I completed the course confidently knowing that I learned a great deal---specifically due to having such a dedicated, genuine, and deeply knowledgeable prof. Highly recommend Prof. Ditty!

Prof. Ditty is a fantastic teacher! He has a very successful DBT practice in Delaware and is brings in a lot of direct clinical research with him. I think he combines the research and practical experience (concrete software to use and when) to inform future practitioners. Very recommended but you gotta like research!

Ditty is a pretty cool guy. He talks about DBT a lot because that is what he works with. We do mindfulness exercise at the beginning of every class. He lectures the whole time, even if he runs out of things to do he makes us sit there. Very rarely do we ever get out early and by early I mean at least 5 mins. He's funny though and very honest.
nice

Professor Ditty is single-handedly improving my perspective on research.  He makes it fun, relevant, and links our learning to subjects we care about. The class is difficult, but he supports us and constantly expresses encouragement. Matthew Ditty is a great professor, one of the best I've taken, and a human being I respect a hell of a lot.
Really boring and arrogant

Matt is such a great professor. I found the material of the class to be rather dry, but it was still my favorite class to attend every week. He typically bring in his own real world experience to help bridge the material to your practice. He is very willing to help students. Don't take the class if you don't want to be challenged!
He is awesome. Very helpful and makes class interesting an fun. He brought his dog into class to prove a point about a theory. Definitely recommend taking him!
Very great professor. He will work with you as long as you are willing to work.

I loved Ditty's quirkiness and the fact that he really cares about his students.  He does tend to be a little sensitive, especially if you challenge him, but he's also very approachable. He's funny and is open to talk with students outside of class.  Definitely recommend taking him.
Good classroom environment, supportive teacher who wants students to understand assignments, open to feedback from students, wants students to do well and be passionate about swrk.

She is the worst teacher I ave ever had. When I had a problem, she would make some excuse why it was my fault, and then I would get in trouble. Every time you had a social problem, she would not help. She is the worst and most uselss teacher ever. When you tell her to talk to someone, she says she will, and then will not  do it.
very bad fox 10/10 math TA

Best TA I've ever had!  Extremely cogent and well versed in the material.  Available and helpful during office hours. Abundantly clear he knows his stuff and enjoys the subject matter.  He makes 8 AM recitations a joy (not to mention easy on the eyes, the Indian Jones of the mathematics department).
Terribly difficult class, and the professor is a terrible explainer to boot.

What does he want for a test answer, the world may never know. Get ready to write proofs with "assume not" turns of phrase. I got As in all my comp sci courses at Penn but this one. He came in the day after a test with his hair straight up and muttered to the class "you did not study". I even got book answers from homework that were marked wrong.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Class is hard, but he did a good job!

Dr. Reese is a dedicated, funny, and passionate professor. He really wants you to succeed and gives you the tools to do so, such as frequent office hours, non-graded homework problems, and review sessions. It is up to the student to take advantage of this, though. Quizzes every week keep you on your toes and the midterms are challenging!

Dr. Reese is an engaging lecturer and good teacher who sincerely wants you to understand the material. However, his class is stressful: a quiz every week, plus 3 midterms. Doing homework is essential to learning physics, but may not help you on his exams. He likes to make you solve things algebraically, which becomes kind of a nightmare!

Great guy and was always available to help out, during office hours as well as outside the class. My lack of prior knowledge (which was kinda required) made it a hard class for me. I dint particularly like his lecture style either - the long pauses kinda made me zone out. He was really nice and encouraging every time I spoke to him.
Very knowledgeable, explains things well. Tries to keep everyone on track and go with a flow that's comfortable for students. Nice guy, too.
Really nice guy! Knows his stuff!

Poor communication of concepts in lecture and intentionally obscure tests. His lack of clear instruction is disappointing, as the course could be much better than currently construed. Although most test material comes from lecture, the book is far better in clarifying ideas.

Prof Krishnan was a nice person, but the lectures were just complete gibberish at times. I think I took the first class he ever taught, and it was pretty clear. I passed the course without understanding a single thing I learned all year, it was complete gibberish to me.

TJ is a great professor. He is funny, passionate, and engaging. He has a brilliant mind. However, like many brilliant minds, he can be disorganized. Don't expect quick responses to emails and you'll have to really stay on top of him to get your papers back. And get ready for group projects! He also really values participation in class.

The course seems great, until Lampson decided not to answer questions. Grade fully dependent on his subjective perception of how much you understood and a report. The final report topic was cleared by him, but when he graded it he decided he didn't understand it. Horrible professor, hopefully will not stay at Penn.

Quantum I. She was extremely willing to help and teach, but she just couldn't. Decided to teach our class to a more difficult level than the grad level class, no one understood the class at all. Very confusing.

Definitely a theorist, lots of math. I loved this guy, one of the best Physics professors at Penn. And extremely, extremely helpful during office hours. However, I know others in the class didn't like him. He's a bit old guard but the biggest genius in the Penn Physics department. Tears people to shreds during seminars.

Vijay is a theorist, and he throws equations on the board filling a chalkboard a minute. But he explains very little and is completely unavailable and does not hold office hours. I also felt that Vijay is extremely subjective and condescending. His graduate students know him to be extremely intense, which is good.

Prof has no VC experience.  Majority of classes are spent discussing things that do not seem relevant. Homework doesn't mirror what's covered in class.  Material also doesn't follow the textbook or mirror those covered in other sections or by other professors. Tons of work, not a lot of gain.

Prof has no experience in VC. Class material irrelevant for tests and assignments. He insists this is a quant class, but we spend most of class time talking about non-quant stuff, not learning how the financial pieces come together (why bother testing us on random quant stuff if we're not going to go over it in depth?). Avoid. A lot of busy work.

He is great and willing to help international students with our expression problems! The content of this course is pretty easy for students from other backgrounds like me. Before his class I had no mechanical engineering background but it is still easy to get an A in his class. Just read the Moran's and listen to the class.
I liked him a lot and liked his sense of humor.The class was very expository. It was more or less a seminar type class: very enlightening.
I really liked the professor and the course. And he had a sense of humor that I appreciated.
Great Professor. Enjoyed his class!!!
Markets the class to people outside of engineering, but it is clearly only intended for someone with an engineering background. I'm sure its great for them, but not a business school student.
Sort of a tough grader but an absolutely lovely and helpful person.
Tough but great!

Pace was too fast for a class of less than ten first semester freshmen in their first college language class. By the end of the semester I didn't look both ways crossing the street in hopes I'd get hit by a bus on the way to this class

He is a good music teacher. Brilliant composer. Just make sure you don't miss any class and actually do the homework. Most of the students who do not do well in his class are the ones who never come to class and never do the homework. Some students only show up for tests and as a result they don't do well. This is a serious course.

Hey you, yeah you... kid who thinks this will be an easy way to breeze through the college's formal reasoning requirement. DON'T DO IT. Out of five courses (two being grad level politics courses), this was, by far, the most stressful. The tests are overly difficult and no partial credit is given even for questions that require multiple steps.

A really great professor. He really knows the material and is very good at making it accessible. Equally as important, he is very easy to talk to and he is willing to work with students who come to him for help. I would definitely recommend him.
Awesome teacher and really understands you as a student, although, she might be a tough grader unless you know your stuff.
Good Professor very helpful and great person. She is always responsive and helpful and leads a great class discussion. The class in the museum is quite fun.

This professor is the BEST. She really knows her stuff, but she never makes you feel inferior. She not only welcomes your thoughts, but she also seems to analyze them as critically as she would her own. How refreshing. Try to be present for her lectures! Not only will you love them, but they are VERY important if you want to do well in the class.

Very good lecturer, clear, explains very well, can easily keep you interested for 3 hour long lecture, discusses with you any questions or concerns you have, etc. You have to keep up with the readings and attend the lectures to not miss the information that the course covers.

Dan is a phenomenal professor. His lectures are clear and engaging and he is very helpful. On more then one occasion I spent thirty plus minutes in his office with him working through argument reconstructions. He'd give me feedback as I made breakthroughs and help me out if I was stuck. This is how philosophy is supposed to be.
Professor Singer really cares about the subject matter and that shines through in class lectures. He's a tough grader but his feedback made me a better writer.

Tremendous scientist, didn't seem to have any interest in teaching. Powerpoint slides were photocopied from the textbook. The textbook often contained wrong information or incorrect calculations, so piecing together what, precisely, was true was nearly impossible.

Dr. Rarig was a great organic chemistry instructor who had ample amounts of time outside of class from office hours on a biweekly basis to review sessions prior to exams on the weekend.  He does not hand out easy grades but he is not in any way unfair.

I took this CHEM241 and CHEM242 with Dr. Rarig and I can say his class is not easy, but that is what is generally expected with an Organic Chemistry class. He is extremely dedicated and knowledgeable about the subject.  I would recommend him to others who need to take the class as long as they are willing to put in the time and effort.

Class was informative and plenty of supplemental instruction (eg office hours and review sessions) was offered. Tests were representative of the material covered in class and included in the provided problem sets. Problem sets were challenging and helpful.

Most of class time is him drawing complicated mechanisms on the board and not explaining them. We can learn that in the book. He rarely does examples, although he got better at that. Class time is basically only useful for hints for exams. His exams are impossible. He was also not accommodating when I missed class time while in the hospital.

Extremely bad professor, very hard to follow his lectures. Keep going in circles what makes even harder to understand, easy to get lost. Jumps from one topic to another. Acts as if he is the smartest in the world! Aside, unfair grader! Maximum what you can expect is B if you work REALLY HARD! Class average is C, C-. DON'T TAKE HIM! Save your GPA!!!

Andy is a great clinician. This class will initially be frustrating to those of us who like structure, but he is open to feedback on this and you will need to adjust your expectations. Go with the flow, read the book for your own edification, and Andy can be a great resource to you, too.
What a waste of time... unless you are into being treated like a child, being called "honey" or enjoy his puppet shows.
He's quirky and a little dated, but his stories are awesome.
Does not follow the expectations as laid out in the syllabus. The professor does not explain the theories of the class well or in a clear fashion as described in the text.
Carly's passion for teaching and social justice is inspirational. Her teaching style is the perfect balance of levity and honesty. Absolutely  take her class!

Carly was my favorite professor my first semester of my MSW. She connects with her students on a deeper level, and cares about the material. I was inspired by her from day 1 and looked forward to going to class everyday. If you're interested in clinical social work and happen to be a feminist, I highly recommend taking her courses.

Not conducive to different styles of learning. Felt like she was not into the material, after all she is not a professor or a teacher, but rather a social worker. I don't think her place is in a graduate classroom. Superficial knowledge of the material.
Classes are boring and her teaching style just didn't match with my learning style.

Prof. Weinstein is a very nice man who knows his stuff and will go out of his way to help you. That said, for 90% of students, including myself, this class is a frantic struggle to keep your head above water. Class is heavily curved. I ended up with about a 60 in the class and pulled an A-.

Weinstein knows this stuff flawlessly and this causes him to have trouble explaining things to students because to him, all of it just makes perfect sense. This is known as one of the harder classes in the college and math majors routinely drop it. Tests can contain schemata that are an order of magnitude more difficult than in class. Be cautious.

Facts first: He's always on time, posts notes before class, expects you to pay attention, responds within 24 hours of you email him( no office hours). Facts aside, he is a very kind professor, passionate about his field, and is very patient with challenging questions and students. He may need a bit more organization but I highly recommend him.

This class was one of my favorites! Professor Eckmann has a terrific sense of humor and he uses it to keep us focused during the lengthy and prolonged hours of his lecture. One of the most memorable moments in class EVER was when he did his elephant impression.

Very inspirational-tells us constantly it is our DESTINY to win. Yet he is about as clear as a VW beetle filled with smoke.  Easy to pay attention to- his voice is like a wizard's. Kind of seems like the type of professor who would walk through wet cement without realizing it.  excellent class though, you should take it.

Doctor Professor was a very vibrant lecturer, knocking questions out of the park like a softball. Runs through slides like a graceful GAZELLE! Lots of Coursework though, my friend Fred practically died under the workload. As long as you're not dumber than a bag of  hammers and put in some effort, you should get an A.
This class was about Bioengineering. Take it!
great instructor
Joe is by far the best instructor I had at Penn. He's funny and makes it interesting. He makes things easy to understand and he really knows what he's talking about.

Prof MCK is one of the best professors ive ever had. Like seriously awesome. Shes so clear with her expectations, and her TAs are great. You have to put in a lot of work, but like, she makes it as survivable as possible.
Awful and condescending professor.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough Grader--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment_Rating: Pray you get a decent TA. They do all the grading and are instructed to give everyone an average grade unless you do something extraordinary, so expect to get a B. This class is a whole new level of nightmare on top of the horror that is Penn organic chemistry. Take it somewhere else if you can.
Professor Wilker is a brilliant German classicist. She is intermittently funny, constantly engaging, and sincerely invested in her students.

Professor Heller teaches sustainability in business.  She is a master of her material & presents it in a clear manner.  I learned about circular value chains and how we can increase efficiency & profit by accounting for all inputs and outputs of a business. Her dedication to her students continues after the course ends. She is a great prof & person

Trudy Heller is a wonderful professor. She is passionate about her subject and just as willing to help students find their paths as she is willing to put in the work planning her courses. I recommend her without reservation

Professor Heller is among the best professors that I've encountered at Penn. Her knowledge of the subject matter, tremendous wealth of real-world experience and exceptional passion for sustainability made this course a very beneficial learning experience. I appreciated that Professor Heller frequently facilitates open discussion in each lecture.

Professor Heller served as my advisor and was wonderful to work with. She provided  critical feedback to help me frame my research and my final document. She made herself available to meet as often as I needed and she reviewed numerous drafts. I also took a sustainable business course with Prof. Heller (phenomenal readings and class discussions!).
TA Ben-Ali is funny and clear. She is really smart and it shows. Always reply's to emails quickly and is always helpful. She's a Ph-d student and a role model.

Professor Feldman was an excellent lecturer with some solid insights. He was also a kind mentor; he even met up with another student and me a couple of years after our course to take us on a tour of the Old City of Jerusalem and discuss some of his latest research.

I took the hydrid intensive section with Dr. Ledwith. She was knowledgable and insightful as we discussed case studies. Fair amount of reading but if you didn't wait until the last minute to prepare, it was doable and each reading was intentional. There were some minor tech mishaps but she made herself available via email if we had questions.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Inspirational--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Really enjoyed Mental Health Diagnostics. If you're looking to go into agency work or community mental health, Professor Ledwith has a ton of experience and very deep knowledge of a variety of treatment modalities. Would highly recommend for any clinical classes. The lectures are pretty good, but ASK QUESTIONS -- I learned so much from her tangents

I took Mental Health Diagnostics with Prof. Ledwith. She's very experienced and really knows her stuff! She's pretty personable and invested in helping you understand the content. Expectations for assignments are clear. She's not a tough grader. Though, lectures are a little dry.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: I think this school should make monthly UAs mandatory.
Unapproachable
Dr. LaFortune was a great professor.  The class discussions are always really good and she's really understanding and caring.

Would not take this classagain.  She wasn't the greatest teacher and lacked facilitation skills that are necessary to teach a class with so much discussion.  I don't feel like she was that understanding and you got docked for every absence even if you had a written excuse.  I would say it was an easy A, so if that's what you're looking for take it.

Professor LaFortune is very intelligent on the subject matter and translates that really well for all the students in class. She allows students to do projects and papers on topics they find most interesting. She is big into participation so don't take the class if that's not your thing! Great class discussions and really interesting readings.
knows the subject and teaches it well gives out extra credit in exams
Tough grader, likes to ignore "basic" concepts and go over lots of proofs, somewhat confusing. Drinks lots of coffee in class, also hilarious.
He's a fair but tough grader,he definitely knows his math well and truly cares about teaching quality.A bit quirky though.
Explained calculus with theory , covered more than what I"ve learned in AP cal. u have to work ur butt off but definite worth it. also don't buy the txt was never used.
Enthusiastic and fair.
One of the worst professors I've ever had.  Does not care about students.  Ridiculous curve system

Has an inane curve where he gives an A to the highest score and adjusts from there, so if one person gets a higher score than everyone else he ruins it for everyone else.  Had the second highest grade in his class, was a B+. Generally a bad communicator of information and seems disinterested in students and teaching.
I LOVE HER she always helped me and was really nice
She is awful.  I was so stressed the whole time during this class

An awesome teacher.  Her daughter always is there and is so funny.  She is a little confusing, but wants the best for you.  You get to work at her house studying if you want.  Also she takes us on field trips to doctors without boundaries.
One of the best teachers of had at Penn. I definitely wish there were more of her caliber at this institution. Informitive and helpful. Always there for us when we need her.

Professor gave extremely convoluted directions on major projects and assigned a ton of busy work. If professor noted that attendance was low she would make childish and petty comments to those in attendance.  Slow to grade work and always had an excuse.

Though I like Dr. Cnaan as a person, I had trouble with his teaching style. Assigns way too many readings and does not discuss/connect them to class lectures. I often did not feel prepared to complete the papers based on where we were in class lectures. He was a flexible grader and was open to student feedback about the amount of assignments.

Class is lecture heavy but some small group in-class projects. To get an A, you must produce quality papers and attend virtually every class. Complete the readings. If you don't, he will be able to tell when he reads your papers. If you don't spend enough time writing them, don't be surprised when your grade reflects that. your grade  your effort

Class gets completely derailed by his pedantic tangents. Does not allow you to go to the bathroom once class has started. Argumentative and caustic, and not in a productive way. Great historian and researcher. Not a good teacher.
He's the best explainer of complex math problems in the universe!
Great Professor
Inspirational pain research

Dr. Polomano holds generally interesting lectures&has great guest speakers. However, outside the classroom she is well known as a student-hating robot. Her main cause is kicking students out of the faculty couch areas, she is very passionate about that. I cannot imagine her ever being a nurse. Utterly lacking in compassion. Interesting research tho
Accent is strong, but he's extremely helpful, funny, and a great mathematician!
She is an awesome teacher.  She knows talking about.  She is my favorite teacher ever.
Was an awesome teacher.  Took us on a lot of field trips.  Very hard class, made you work for everything.

Professor Pien is easy to understand and helpful. He makes sure you actually learn Hindi. His class is interesting and well structured. He assigns homework that can take awhile, but it isn't busy work and he is a benevolent grader. Overall, I am learning a lot. I have taken a variety of Hindi courses over the years and his is the best by far.

Professor Pien is an excellent language teacher. He assigns a LOT of homework, but is easy on grading if you can't finish it for some reason (but be sure your reason is good). He's funny and very willing to explain any questions. He makes sure that not only the language but South Asian culture is explored in class.

Dr. Guillen is an incredible teacher and is an excellent resource outside of class as well. Super informative/engaging structure, I loved the homework assignments as well as the opportunity for civilized dialogue and debate amongst peers in class during a contentious time in America. Definitely take a class with him for a super positive experience.

The man is just incapable of getting to the point or cutting through the irrelevant detail to make an incisive point. It's probably cultural but he just drones and drones, most of what he says is irrelevant, and even the relevant details are so incomplete and so arbitrarily derived that they may as well be meaningless.

Professor Guilln is the best professor I've ever had. He makes the material accessible and fascinating. Not only is his accent absolutely divine, but he is a really good teacher who values students' input. Definitely take a class from him.

Ching-Li Chai is horrible. He doesn't teach what you need for the final and he is impossible to understand. If you get him, you need to switch out. Everyone in my class works extremely hard to understand the material, but he makes it so difficult.

Great professor. Lectures are engaging with good PPT. Dr. Cranz has a great sense of humor and makes the class enjoyable.  Workload is not too excessive, and written assignments were interesting.  I recommend doing the reading and taking notes, or you will struggle with the quizzes.  Overall, Dr. Cranz is great. Take her course, do the work, enjoy!
Supportive professor
flaky; huge ego; laughs at her own jokes; ambiguous; no clear directions; subjective; spasmic; does not state positionality; disorganized; not very interested/invested in the course

Yuko is a wonderful professor. Very kind and supportive. Her rich knowledge and clear organization makes her class really useful for everybody. She's also very selective in choosing reading materials, which will help you a lot when you need to write a paper. If you're a TESOL student at GSE, you must take one class with Yuko!

This course taught me how to synthesize 100+ pages of texts from several sources into 500 words. Dr. Hornberger is an amazing professor. Her class is tough, but you will learn so much about the topic.

Nancy is so distinguished and insightful with a very adorable personality. Taking her class is one of the best things I've ever done at GSE. The class is pretty reading-intensive, but what you gain from it is beyond your imagination.

Best professor ever!  She gave me lots of feedback on my papers which helped me improve my writing. She made the very complex subject  of research easy  to understand. Her classes were entertaining but very interactive so don't expect to just sit there.

Amazing professor. Very experienced and caring social worker. She's worked in the field for a long time and really knows her stuff. She expects you to know your stuff too but you will learn a lot. Best class I have ever taken.

She is the WORST! She is unorganized, only reads from PPs, and she doesn't prepare you for the final exam. She constantly changes assignments and never remembers what she has said. Her participation points are based on whether she likes you. She appears calm and then suddenly snaps, she needs medication! Oh, and she hates students of color.

Incredible professor who cares a lot about his students and his class. While not everything is explained thoroughly in lecture, a better understanding of concepts can be achieved by reading the textbook, which lecture closely adheres to (thereby obviating the need to read the textbook). I would recommend taking his class 10/10

Professor Kane is a great teacher. He is very passionate about what he teaches, and tries to make the information as interesting as possible.  Class consists of 3 midterms, and a lab portion. Lab includes 5 take home quizzes attendance points, and a lab practical.  Study the lecture material really well, an A is definitely doable. Loved the class
It's a class that ought to be taken for ease of workload and simplicity of the course objectives
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: One of the best professors in Wharton. He makes complex Statistical material easy to understand, and he is always available to meet to discuss the course.

Ewens is such a nice teacher, I transferred into his class two weeks late into the semester and he immediately made time to meet with me and teach me how to use JMP and catch me up on the basics of the class everyone else got the first day. He gave me unlimited time to make up the homework and proceeded to be an excellent, thorough teacher!
ratingTags_Rating: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment_Rating: The class isn't super hard, but he's pretty confusing when explaining more complicated concepts that are related to hypothesis testing. The exams aren't too awful, but make sure you study the notes he gives out because he loves conceptual questions.
One of the best classes I have taken at Penn. I would highly recommend this course to anyone who wants to learn more about the Ottoman Empire.
A great professor. He is clearly very engaged in his subject and interested to hear his student's ideas. A good sense of humor also helps in a three-hour long course.

Worst class I've ever taken. Professor was a terrible lecturer - relied on powerpoint slides that were hard to follow and cold-called students to answer questions about topics that were not properly explained. The way he presented material both lacked mathematical rigor and failed to nurture conceptual understanding.

Melissa is a disrespectful, sarcastic, dry, and overall terrible instructor. She does not instruct class. She facilitates a discussion based on the reading. I did not learn very much in this class. I went to administration about her and they told me that there are always a few bad apples, but it wasn't the first complaint they received on her.

He's an amazing story teller. Going to lecture is like going to the movies almost. I don't even need to read the texts (even though they are helpful) because he summarizes everything so well and really gives a good picture of what things were like. He's super dedicated to his study too and it shows. Super passionate about what he does.
She is very friendly and easy going. She provides clear instructions when discussing assignments.

Provided very interesting perspective to students in the class from an extensive and unique background experience, which made the material very engaging. Converses often with students to help them grasp and think critically about what is covered. Overall, great experience, and would recommend the course and the professor.

You had to show up at least for the presentations and the weekly quizzes; the rest, you could miss and still do fine in the class. It was definitely necessary to do the readings in order to do well on the quizzes. The information was interesting, but the lectures could get a bit slow and repetitive at times, and it was often easy to just zone out.
Welton was pretty good!

Political Psychology was by far the most interesting class I took this semester and Welton Chang definitely played a role in that. He made the material interesting and engaging. It wasn't an easy class but I never felt lost or too confused because the professor and the TA were both very responsive and helpful.

Welton is very knowledgeable and passionate about Superforecasting. He also has a fascinating background (spanning both the public and private sector), and uses it to develop interesting simulations.  Hes also very friendly and approachable. He gives great advice, and I wouldnt hesitate to take a course by him again. I hope we stay in touch!

Welton was my TA/associate professor for the MGMT276. Welton has an awesome background in intelligence and was able to make any topic interesting. Welton was also extremely easy to work with, and always provided relevant and easy to understand  help when asked. Welton was an excellent professor!

Welton went above and beyond to make the power points enjoyable by finding humerus comics or cartoons that were based on the information we were learning. He also had a very impressive range of skills and could offer helpful feedback for all of the group discussions. Welton had a very well respected opinion.

Welton was a great TA for MGMT 276.  He has interesting ideas and challenges students to approach forecasts in new ways.  I appreciated his feedback throughout the class; discussing ideas with him helped me to refine how I think about problems.
Welton is supportive, accessible, and overall a great pleasure to learn from.
Welton had a lot of worldly knowledge and experience to draw from to make class more interesting. He was also really understanding of personal conflicts that came up for me during the semester.

Welton was extremely helpful throughout the course. When I was having trouble with group assignments he was understood and did his best to work with me. In class he helped students to see subject matter in a new way, through engaging activities.

Welton was a great as a teacher in the class this year. Firstly, due to thevalue his insights and expertise gave to students in a very specifc and competitive subject. But what was great about Welton, was the fact he was willing to discuss, and spend time, explaining his reasoning and forcasting methods to students. He created a welcoming environme
Brings his professional experience as a military intelligence analyst to the classroom in a very interesting way.
Really hands on with the students. Only wish he had more of him so that he could spend more time with everyone.
He was super helpful and definitely seemed to take a deep interest in the class.

Always had something constructive to say when help was requested.  Responded to e-mails very promptly with specific and clear instructions where required.  Assisted Professor Tetlock in the construction of clear and entertaining slides for the course.
really helped me to develop a more open mind and approach forecasting in a productive way
Depth of knowledge about US policy and international affairs adds value to class content

Welton was an extremely valuable part of my class experience. He often offered his knowledge as extensions of the material, connecting the in-class readings and discussions to his real world experiences. He was clear in class and via email, and highly responsive to any questions and concerns.
Very quality course, engaging as well. Welton made himself very available to answer questions and was open to opposing ideas.
Welton made the class applicable, fun and engaging.  He has a great ability to connect with students and his care and passion for the subject show tremendously.

Welton was the TA in my class on political psychology/superforecasting.  He was extremely helpful in explaining the material and challenging our thought process to gain different perspectives and be more accurate. He was also a helpful liaison between the students and the professor.

Welton is very knowledgeable and lectures in a way that makes the information very easy to understand. He is very concise and one of the best teachers I have had at Wharton. The group exercises that he had us do in class were very well organized and extremely useful. I had an amazing semester with Welton, and I wish I could take the class again.

Very clear and effective communicator. It is difficult to not be engaged while Welton is speaking as he inherently demands attention give his enthusiasm for course material. I highly recommend any course in which he is involved in any sort of capacity.

Great real world experience that was directly relevant to the material.  Was always available to answer extra questions after lecture.  Replied to email queries extremely quickly.  Welton made the material relevant and interesting. Best course I have taken at Penn.

Welton Chang may definitely be considered one of the best TAs I have ever had at Penn. When he led lectures or activities, they always turned out to be extremely interesting and engaging. The class was also fascinated by his previous job experiences. I noticed that some students would go to him for career advice as well.

Walton always made himself available both in and outside of class. If I asked a question over email, I'd get a quick and concise response. During group exercises, Welton attended to everyone, offering unique perspectives and answers to questions. Additionally, Welton's attitude towards the subject matter inspired me to work hard in the course.

Welton was great in office hours and was helpful during class when we had questions about our group project. His feedback was very clear and helpful and I liked that he was really passionate about his field.

Welton is extremely intelligent and well-versed with the subject matter. He is very approachable and tends to answer any questions you have with care and clarity, giving useful and constructive feedback.
Welton was amazing and he definitely made the course more enjoyable. He is highly knowledgeable, patient and is always willing to assist students.
His classes are pretty boring, but if you understand the exercises he gives, should be an easy A+. Not a lot of work needed to pass the class with an excellent grade.
She is a fair grader, while also providing useful feedback on assignments. Pam is awesome and worth taking again!

Dr. Szczygiel is amazing! She is genuinely passionate about the work that she does. She is supportive and understanding. Taking her class on self-care is helpful and exciting. MSW students can easily get burnt out, but this class helps. There are group assignments which is fine. Reflection journals are weekly.

She is one of my favorite professors at this school. She makes the material interesting and engaging and I always looked forwards to her classes. She is very accommodating and understanding, and her assignments are not difficult.
Dr. Wattenbarger was a very nice professor with a pretty clear course and grading structure
The course material is easy, but she makes everything so complicated!!!

She is a very friendly teacher and you will get a good grade in the class if you listen to all of her suggestions and make the correct edits in your work. Such a precious Scottish lady, really knows her stuff and gives very clear and concise derivations. He  has difficulty explaining material to a class and one-on-one. Marsha is the best professor I have ever had (and I have 4 degrees from 3 universities). SHE IS A REAL HUMAN BEING--Not the typical Ivy League arrogant instructor. Professor did not show up to 2 of 8 evening classes and gave no notice of her absence leading to students going to campus and paying for parking only to not have class. Awesome!

great! lol

Professor Shams! I took two courses with you, one in fall 2017 and one spring 2018. You have been a great source of inspiration in my life at Penn. Professor Al Filreis is both passionate and well versed in poetry. Areas of study as subjective and often abstract as this one require just such a teacher. Al is very involved in the day activities of the class.  He was involved daily in discussion board and our FB Modpo group discussions.  I found myself immersed in the material presented in the class and the lessons and insights gleaned from Modpo have carried over into my day to day life.

Al Filreis made the course of Modern and Contemporary American Poetry incredibly interesting. What is very valuable in the work of Professor Filreis is that he tries not to leave without the answer any question, what could seem impossible in MOOCs.

He helps one see poets and writers in a new light as if they had been partially hidden in chiaroscuro until then. He expounds his ideas in socratic fashion, so that one comes to understand what one otherwise may have missed about their worth. Most of all he helps one feel they can be part of what literature is all about.
Great course. Fabulous professor. Awesome TAs.

He provided a challenging and satisfying overview of modern and contemporary American poetry.  His use of a roundtable discussion rather than lecture format provided an high-interest learning environment.

He is fantastic and demanding (and deserving) of one's best efforts.
