Make sure to attend all OOH and review sessions.

Discussion on homework is strictly prohibited, and TAs are not allowed to help with homework in any matter. Many times we need clarifications for very poorly worded questions but cannot be helped. Grading rubic is never clear, you get 0/10 using an alternate solution and write essays to seek regrade. High school maths deliberately made complicated.
His explanation is not clear at all, I am having a difficult time understanding his discrete math course
Wonderful professor, I think he is very fun and does in good job in teaching very difficult class.
Most of the assignments seem confusing

You must answer questions following the template the professor provided otherwise you will lose some points. For example, you will be punished for failing to mention some keywords even you get everything correct.
Awful

Professor Tannen does not get nearly enough credit. Many students who take this course lack strong Mathematical foundations, but that is in no way his fault. His lectures are clear. His office hours are extensive. He often goes overtime to ensure that no student questions are left unanswered. Reading comprehension is a must at a Master's level.

Terrible lectures do not set you up for success in homeworks or exams. Expect to learn mostly from outside sources and expect to only be able to do the homework after grilling the TAs for hints and pointers on how to approach the problems.
Professor Tannen is mean-spirited and tetchy.
Professor Tannen is abysmal and his grading is inconsistent and unfair. He's also mean spirited and tetchy.
Class is not set up well, the lectures are old and error-riddled and the professor does not seem open to changing the non-conducive learning style of this course.

While he is a smart man, that does not mean he should be a professor. 

His way with words could be considered lacking as his comments come off rude or sometimes cruel for pretty simple questions.  Very stuck in his ways.

For this course in MCIT he does not tends to realize he is teaching CS students and not people pursuing a Math Masters.

Such an awful teacher, he teaches a math course but does not actually teach you. He expects you to pick everything up yourself, with no clear elaboration on the class material. He chooses to make things harder than they should be (especially in terms of language), so you are tested more on question comprehension rather than discrete math itself.

The topics he explains and the ones he asks you to solve are no where related. I guess he is expecting us to learn math ourselves and not actually teach. The assignments are poorly worded you end up scratching your head to make sense of simple English than actually solving problems. Senseless questions poor grammar. You will end up as content creat

Great professor. Available to help students - always kept his open office hours going until there were no more questions, even if the scheduled time had elapsed. Felt challenged but never hopeless about the class, and really felt I had earned my grade at the end. I wish he taught more MCIT classes!
Great professor. Engaged with the students and clearly wants to help them to thoroughly understand the material. All the material has been very relevant to our follow on core classes.
Cold conversation. Doesn't care about the students' experience.
Great prof.
Utterly useless class.  The only good news is she doesn't care if you spend the entire class on the internet, and I was able to learn what she was supposed to teach from youcubed.
Would not recommend any course with this professor at any level.
Unfathomable amounts of reading, extremely long essays, terrible TAs, confusing lectures. Would never take a class with him again.

Possibly one of the most dynamic, intelligent, interesting and provocative professors at Penn. You get from Vitalis what you give - give a lot, you'll get nothing less than gold. Highly recommended no matter what your major - take his class. Do the readings. Argue. I'm just sorry I didn't work harder in the class, he is worth it.
Vitalis is helpful,  but his classes are by no means easy to get A's in.

My experience with professor Goodman was less than ideal. Her teaching style lacked clarity and organization, making it difficult to follow lessons. Additionally, she would not allow questions during lectures which hindered my progress. Overall, it was a disappointing experience that left me feeling unprepared for more advanced music studies.
He is one true caring, devoted educator who changed my way of thinking and learning, and eventually my life. :)
Amazing prof, really helps you truly understand the proofs behind mathematics

Class was interesting, inspiring, and very broad introduction to modern geometry-topology, with topics ranging from differential forms and tangent bundles to knot theory. Main problem was that the breadth of subject material and at times unreasonable amount of homework did not permit time to learn proofs in-depth. Maybe assign group work per topic.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: He's even worse than last semester. Doesn't prove anything that can't be done by just drawing a picture. By not proving anything he can keep a very fast pace, but keeping up with the textbook is impossible (unless you don't want to understand proofs i.e. you don't want to understand at all). Please go teach undergrads as they don't want rigor.

A problem with the course is assigning so much homework that there isn't enough time to read the text. This is a problem, because of the lack of rigor. For someone already familiar with the material, I would guess the course is pretty ideal. For everyone else the course is far from it. The 2nd year grads also seem to either love it or hate it.

My favorite course this semester! The class covers too much material to go through the proofs in class, so we spend most of the class time with examples; proofs are assigned as homework reading or exercises. (There are good proofs in the literature but few good examples!) Decent lecturer. Looking forward to 601!

Gives no definitions and very few rigorous proofs. Ignores the fact that a 1st year graduate course in differential geometry is supposed to teach tools and techniques with the goal of being able to use them in other fields. His course is equivalent to teaching grad cosmology out of Hawkins' A Brief History of Time. Useless and worst course ever.
When I had Professor Gluck, he took particular care to make sure that every student understood what we were learning. I thought he was excellent.
really nice guy, tries to keep class animated, but just not possible with the material
Rude and disrespectful

After watching an episode of The Food that Built America I started craving a Blimpie sub since I had not had one in over 20 years! she said the n word in class and then tried to explain it when someone said they were uncomfortable because "she's a historian"

She is one of the most disrespectful and arrogant individual I have ever met. She yells in office hours for no reason without providing any helpful feedback she sits there calling you a lier. In one class, she insisted that she is a better speaker of a foreign language than a native speaker in the class (she does not speak this language).

I enjoyed her classes, and was inspired by her work, but having her serve on my dissertation committee was a nightmare. She is known for yelling at students and even research assistants in her office, and made clear that asking for feedback was a serious imposition on her time. Go to her lectures, read her books, but find more humane mentors.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Loomba is a knowledgeable scholar. You can glean that from reading her many books. As a teacher, however, her pedagogy is non-existent, her feedback is harsh, oddly personal, and often unclear, and she gets overly defensive and even offended when disagreed with. In private, she'll make comments that cut deeply. Beware.

By far the most disrespectful professor I have ever encountered in school. Nasty in office hours. She is not willing to help, clarify, or provide HELPFUL feedback to students. I regret taking her class, and I would not recommend anyone to take her course.

She is awesome. Most students say that about professors that are either easy or laid back, (she isn't either one of those things), but what she is is brilliant. Amazingly smart, and will challenge you ideas and how you think. SHE IS NOT RUDE or disrespectful to students in class or in office hours. Don't expect to be coddled but to be challenged.
Extremely RUDE.  Not as brilliant as others have made her out to be.  Class was fairly easy, rather boring.  Her angry rants should not be mistaken for a genuine interest in the subject matter.
Can be very intense but totally inspirational.
brilliant.
By far the most disrespectful English Professor I have ever had.  Does not seem to respect other cultures, either.
A shame such an intelligent person cannot be as gifted in dealing with people respectfully.  Exceedingly arrogant and not worth learning from.

I added her class only to find that she had singled me out in a crude, malicious tone during the first five minutes for adding the class late and not knowing what book we would be using that day.  Other students, as well as professors, later approached me saying that they felt sorry for me and that she was just usually "mean" and "judgemental".

She is the reason I didnt become an English major like I thought I would Freshman year. She is really cruel in office hours, like another poster said. In class she is interesting and enjoyable, but she really says hurtful and rude things to you in personal meetings.

Prof. Loomba is amazing.  She takes you not just through the texts, but the surrounding contexts, reading cultures as well as plays, poetry, etc.  She really challenges you to think, to attack questions is ways you never have before.  Plus she is amazingly nice, and brought cookies for us on more than one occasion.  Take a class with her.
amazing
Brilliant and fair.
very smart and interesting in class.  not available very much outside of class but her excitement for intellectual material is contagious.

Great in class, but NASTY in office hours. No respect for students' intelligence, efforts, commitment. Assignments unclear. Takes offence and goes on the attack if you ask her to clarify. Tells students she doesn't have time to help them.  Her general message is that you should just give up.

Dr. Jeoung is a really great professor who cares about her students. She is very clear about her grading and constantly reminds us that she is always willing to provide extra help. The class is a lot of work but isn't hard, and she tells us why what we are doing is important, so we stay motivated. Highly recommend her class!

She is such a sweet professor and does not grade harshly. She is very lenient and understanding with grading as long as you pay enough attention and stay interested in what she teaches. The workload isn't hefty but you will be doing a lot of reading.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Typically grades based off completion and is very understanding when it comes to assignments and workload.

SPANI 0100: One of the nicest professors I have ever had as a transfer from Syracuse University. I really wish I was able to take SPAN 0200 with her but I don't believe she is teaching next semester. I am writing this comment with the hopes that the Spanish department reads this as well as my course evaluation comments. GIVE HER SPAN 0200 CLASSES!

Profesora Nozaleda is a very caring and thoughtful instructor, and takes the time to meet you where you're at in your learning journey. It is a pretty fast-paced class, so definitely be prepared to attend and participate!

Professor Barreto changed my Penn experience. He is down to earth, funny, relatable, and very knowledgable. This course took an emersion based approach to learning Spanish. The class size was small so everyone got to know each other really well. It was a 9am class, but Professor Barreto kept the energy alive and made it  worth waking up for.
There are no curves.

For lack of a nicer, more mature way of saying it, he sucks. No consideration for students who learn differently and is so adamant that grades don't matter in the end, which just feels like code for "i dont care that im a prof, suck it up."

my experience was very unpleasant. he doesn't explain things clearly and his teaching method did not fit my style of learning. as student's we were forced to teach ourselves through dense and boring text book readings then go to class. he is simply a teacher who does not TEACH. it was impossible for me to pass. he is abstract which doesn't work.
